<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch10-path-integrals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Path Integral Formalism (Dimension 1: Alternative)</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Understand Feynman's path integral as an alternative formulation of quantum mechanics.</li>
      <li>Derive the path integral from the time-slicing procedure.</li>
      <li>Evaluate Gaussian path integrals for the free particle and harmonic oscillator.</li>
      <li>Understand the classical limit and the stationary phase approximation.</li>
      <li>Appreciate why path integrals are the natural language for quantum field theory.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p>The first dimension of our framework concerns the mathematical formalism: operator methods vs. path integrals. Until now, we have worked exclusively with the operator (canonical) formalism—states as vectors, observables as operators, evolution via the Schrödinger equation. This chapter introduces Feynman's path integral, an entirely different but equivalent formulation that provides complementary insight.</p>
    <p>In the path integral formulation, the transition amplitude between two states is computed by summing over all possible paths the particle could take, weighted by <m>e^{iS/\hbar}</m> where <m>S</m> is the classical action. This "democratic" sum over histories makes the classical limit transparent, naturally incorporates gauge invariance, and provides the foundation for quantum field theory.</p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-motivation">
    <title>From Operators to Paths</title>
    <p>The transition amplitude in the operator formalism is:</p>
    <me>
      K(x_f, t_f; x_i, t_i) = \bra{x_f} e^{-i\HH(t_f-t_i)/\hbar} \ket{x_i}.
    </me>
    <p>Feynman's insight: divide the time interval <m>[t_i, t_f]</m> into <m>N</m> small steps of duration <m>\epsilon = (t_f - t_i)/N</m>, and insert complete sets of position states at each intermediate time. In the limit <m>N \to \infty</m>:</p>

    <assemblage xml:id="box-path-integral">
      <title>The Feynman Path Integral</title>
      <me>
        K(x_f, t_f; x_i, t_i) = \int \mathcal{D}[x(t)] \, e^{iS[x(t)]/\hbar},
      </me>
      <p>where <m>S[x(t)] = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} L(x, \dot{x}, t) \, dt</m> is the classical action and <m>L</m> is the Lagrangian. The integral <m>\int \mathcal{D}[x(t)]</m> sums over all paths from <m>(x_i, t_i)</m> to <m>(x_f, t_f)</m>.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>Every path contributes. The classical path—the one satisfying the Euler-Lagrange equations—has stationary action and dominates in the <m>\hbar \to 0</m> limit. Quantum mechanics arises from the interference of neighboring paths.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-derivation">
    <title>Derivation by Time Slicing</title>
    <p>For a particle with Hamiltonian <m>H = p^2/(2m) + V(x)</m>, the propagator for one small time step <m>\epsilon</m> is:</p>
    <me>
      K(x_{j+1}, x_j; \epsilon) \approx \sqrt{\frac{m}{2\pi i\hbar\epsilon}} \exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(\frac{m(x_{j+1}-x_j)^2}{2\epsilon} - \epsilon V\left(\frac{x_{j+1}+x_j}{2}\right)\right)\right].
    </me>
    <p>The full propagator is the product of these short-time propagators, integrated over all intermediate positions:</p>
    <me>
      K = \lim_{N\to\infty} \left(\frac{m}{2\pi i\hbar\epsilon}\right)^{N/2} \int dx_1 \cdots dx_{N-1} \, \exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\sum_{j=0}^{N-1}\left(\frac{m(x_{j+1}-x_j)^2}{2\epsilon} - \epsilon V(x_j)\right)\right].
    </me>
    <p>The exponent converges to <m>iS[x]/\hbar</m> where <m>S = \int L \, dt</m>. This establishes the equivalence of the path integral and operator formulations.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-free-particle">
    <title>The Free Particle Propagator</title>
    <p>For <m>V = 0</m>, the path integral is a Gaussian integral that can be evaluated exactly:</p>
    <me>
      K_{\text{free}}(x_f, t_f; x_i, t_i) = \sqrt{\frac{m}{2\pi i\hbar(t_f-t_i)}} \exp\left[\frac{im(x_f-x_i)^2}{2\hbar(t_f-t_i)}\right].
    </me>
    <p>This is a spreading Gaussian. The classical path <m>x_{\text{cl}}(t) = x_i + (x_f-x_i)(t-t_i)/(t_f-t_i)</m> contributes the action <m>S_{\text{cl}} = m(x_f-x_i)^2/[2(t_f-t_i)]</m>, and the path integral reduces to <m>K \propto e^{iS_{\text{cl}}/\hbar}</m> times a prefactor from fluctuations around the classical path.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-harmonic">
    <title>The Harmonic Oscillator Path Integral</title>
    <p>For <m>V = m\omega^2 x^2/2</m>, the path integral is again Gaussian (the action is quadratic in <m>x</m>):</p>
    <me>
      K_{\text{HO}} = \sqrt{\frac{m\omega}{2\pi i\hbar\sin(\omega T)}} \exp\left[\frac{im\omega}{2\hbar\sin(\omega T)}\left((x_i^2+x_f^2)\cos(\omega T) - 2x_ix_f\right)\right],
    </me>
    <p>where <m>T = t_f - t_i</m>. This reproduces the exact quantum propagator. The energy eigenvalues <m>E_n = \hbar\omega(n+1/2)</m> can be extracted by Fourier transforming in <m>T</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-classical-limit">
    <title>The Classical Limit and Stationary Phase</title>
    <p>In the limit <m>\hbar \to 0</m>, the path integral is dominated by paths near the classical trajectory (stationary phase approximation). Expanding the action around the classical path <m>x_{\text{cl}}(t)</m>:</p>
    <me>
      S[x] = S[x_{\text{cl}}] + \frac{1}{2}\int dt\,dt' \frac{\delta^2 S}{\delta x(t) \delta x(t')} \eta(t)\eta(t') + \cdots,
    </me>
    <p>where <m>\eta(t) = x(t) - x_{\text{cl}}(t)</m>. The leading contribution gives:</p>
    <me>
      K \approx A \cdot e^{iS_{\text{cl}}/\hbar},
    </me>
    <p>where <m>A</m> is a prefactor from Gaussian fluctuations. This shows how classical mechanics emerges: the classical path is the stationary-phase point of the path integral.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-euclidean">
    <title>Euclidean Path Integrals and Tunneling</title>
    <p>By Wick-rotating to imaginary time <m>t \to -i\tau</m>, the oscillatory integrand <m>e^{iS/\hbar}</m> becomes a decaying exponential <m>e^{-S_E/\hbar}</m>, where <m>S_E</m> is the Euclidean action. This makes the integral well-defined and reveals tunneling phenomena.</p>
    <p>The instanton—a classical solution in Euclidean time—describes quantum tunneling between classically disconnected regions. The tunneling amplitude is:</p>
    <me>
      K_{\text{tunnel}} \propto e^{-S_E^{\text{inst}}/\hbar},
    </me>
    <p>where <m>S_E^{\text{inst}}</m> is the instanton action. This technique is essential for understanding tunneling in quantum field theory (e.g., vacuum decay, theta vacua in QCD).</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-field-theory">
    <title>Path Integrals and Quantum Field Theory</title>
    <p>The path integral formulation extends naturally to fields. Replace the particle coordinate <m>x(t)</m> by a field <m>\phi(x,t)</m>, and the action becomes a functional of the field:</p>
    <me>
      Z = \int \mathcal{D}[\phi] \, e^{iS[\phi]/\hbar},
    </me>
    <p>where <m>S[\phi] = \int d^4x \, \mathcal{L}(\phi, \partial_\mu\phi)</m>. This is the starting point for quantum field theory. The path integral naturally:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Handles gauge invariance through gauge-fixing and Faddeev-Popov ghosts</li>
      <li>Generates Feynman diagrams through perturbative expansion</li>
      <li>Connects quantum field theory to statistical mechanics via Euclidean rotation</li>
      <li>Provides the foundation for lattice gauge theory and non-perturbative methods</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-summary">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>The path integral sums over all histories: <m>K = \int \mathcal{D}[x] \, e^{iS[x]/\hbar}</m>.</li>
      <li>It is derived from the operator formalism by time-slicing the evolution operator.</li>
      <li>Free particle and harmonic oscillator have exact Gaussian path integrals.</li>
      <li>The classical limit emerges from stationary phase: classical path dominates as <m>\hbar \to 0</m>.</li>
      <li>Euclidean path integrals (Wick rotation) describe tunneling via instantons.</li>
      <li>Path integrals extend naturally to fields, providing the foundation for QFT.</li>
      <li>Operator and path integral formalisms are equivalent but offer different computational advantages.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch10">
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-free">
      <statement><p>Derive the free-particle propagator by explicitly evaluating the Gaussian integrals in the time-sliced path integral.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-composition">
      <statement><p>Show that the propagator satisfies the composition property: <m>K(x_f,t_f;x_i,t_i) = \int dx\, K(x_f,t_f;x,t) K(x,t;x_i,t_i)</m>.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-ho-energy">
      <statement><p>From the harmonic oscillator propagator, extract the energy eigenvalues by computing <m>\text{Tr}(e^{-i\HH T/\hbar})</m>.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-stationary">
      <statement><p>For a particle in a linear potential <m>V(x) = -Fx</m>, find the classical path and evaluate the path integral exactly.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-double-well">
      <statement><p>Estimate the tunnel splitting in a symmetric double-well potential using the instanton method.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-partition">
      <statement><p>Show that the Euclidean path integral with periodic boundary conditions computes the partition function: <m>Z(\beta) = \int \mathcal{D}[x] \, e^{-S_E[x]/\hbar}</m> with <m>x(\beta\hbar) = x(0)</m>.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exer-ch10-challenge">
      <statement><p><em>Challenge.</em> Derive the Feynman rules for a scalar field theory <m>\mathcal{L} = \frac{1}{2}(\partial\phi)^2 - \frac{1}{2}m^2\phi^2 - \frac{\lambda}{4!}\phi^4</m> from the path integral.</p></statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</chapter>
